<div class="club-history">
    <h1>Arsenal Football Club History</h1>

    <section>
        <h2>The Early Years</h2>
        <p>Arsenal Football Club was founded in 1886 by workers at the Royal Arsenal in Woolwich, London. Originally named Dial Square, the club soon became Woolwich Arsenal and turned professional in 1891.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Moving to North London</h2>
        <p>In 1913, the club moved to Arsenal Stadium in Highbury, North London, and dropped "Woolwich" from its name, becoming simply "Arsenal". This move would define the club's identity for generations to come.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>The Herbert Chapman Era</h2>
        <p>Under the management of Herbert Chapman in the 1930s, Arsenal became one of England's dominant forces, winning five League Championships and two FA Cups. Chapman's innovative tactics and training methods revolutionized the game.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Post-War Success</h2>
        <p>Arsenal continued its success after World War II, claiming several more league titles and FA Cups. The 1970-71 season saw the club achieve its first league and FA Cup double.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>The George Graham Years</h2>
        <p>Under George Graham's management (1986-1995), Arsenal won two more league titles, including the dramatic 1989 title win at Anfield. The club also gained a reputation for its strong defensive play during this period.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>The Wenger Revolution</h2>
        <p>Arsène Wenger's appointment in 1996 ushered in a new era of success and attractive football. Under Wenger, Arsenal won three Premier League titles, including the unbeaten "Invincibles" season of 2003-04, and seven FA Cups.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Emirates Stadium and Modern Era</h2>
        <p>In 2006, Arsenal moved to the state-of-the-art Emirates Stadium. The club has continued to compete at the highest level, maintaining a record of consecutive top-four finishes in the Premier League until 2017.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Transition period</h2>
        <p>Since Wenger's departure in 2018, Arsenal have gone through a period of transition as they try to regain their place among England's elite clubs.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Mikel Arteta</h2>
        <p>Since December 2019, Mikel Arteta has been the head coach. In just three years, he managed to return the faded Arsenal to the title of a top club, which confidently began to force Manchester City to fight for the championship. The team continues to grow and become stronger and stronger. In the 2022-2023 and 2023/2024 seasons, the team took second place at the end of the season. Who knows, perhaps Mikel Arteta will soon bring Arsenal the long-awaited championship title.</p>
    </section>
</div>
